messages.content: 9-1-1, what's your emergency?
We need an ambulance. I'm on Highway 100.
Where on Highway 100?
I don't know. I'm on my way to watch the hospital, but I don't know if I'll make it. I'm trying to get to the next road.
Okay, I'm going to get an ambulance with my partner. Are you by yourself?
No, I have people with me.
Okay. How many weeks pregnant are you?
I'm 37 weeks.
You're 37 weeks? Is this your first pregnancy?
This is my sixth.
Your sixth pregnancy? How far apart are your contractions?
Like every two minutes.
Every two minutes? Okay. Are you still driving?
He's driving.
You need to get off the road.
He missed the light. We're at the junction of P and V.
Okay, you're at the junction of P and V. Stay on the line with me.
I am.
Are you still having a contraction right now?
Yes, very badly. And I have a lot of pressure.
Okay, I don't want you to push, okay?
I'm trying not to.
Alright, just try to wait. The ambulance is on the way.
Okay, thank you.
Let me know when the contraction is done.
Now again.
Okay, breathe with it.
Okay.
Take a deep breath in, and a little breath out.
Okay, I feel a lot of pressure.
Who is with you?
My husband.
Can you put him on the phone for me?
Alright, hold on.
Okay, sir, I want you to lay her down if you can.
Okay, I'm Richie.
Alright, Richie, do you have your hazards on?
Yes.
Is she feeling pressure right now?
Yeah, she's screaming.
Does she have pants or a dress on?
Pants.
Can you take them off of her?
Okay, they're off.
You're doing a great job. Is she having a contraction right now?
I think so.
Okay. Can you see the baby's head?
No, not yet.
Alright. Leave her on her back, and encourage her to breathe.
When she has her next contraction, see if you can see the baby's head.
Okay.
Who's her doctor?
Dr. Potts.
Alright. She's able to breathe right now?
Yes.
Okay. If this is her sixth baby, she knows how to breathe. Make sure she doesn't push.
Oh crap, the head is coming out.
Alright, I'm going to tell you what to do, Richie. Support the baby's head.
Okay, I'm supporting it.
Is the baby completely out?
Yes.
Do you have a clean towel or cloth?
Not really.
Use her pants to wipe off the baby's mouth and nose. Is it a boy or girl?
It's a boy.
Congratulations! Lay the baby on her belly and keep him warm. Don't pull on the cord. Do you have a shoelace?
Yes.
Tie the umbilical cord about 6 inches from the baby. Just tie, don't cut.
Okay, done.
How's the baby?
He's doing good.
Has the afterbirth come out?
No, not yet.
Alright, the ambulance should be there soon. Congratulations!
Thank you.
You're welcome. Stay with her until they arrive.
9-1-1, what's your emergency?
I need an ambulance, I'm on Highway 100, somewhere between T and V.
Where exactly on 100?
I just went through Highway T and V as in Victor.
So you're west of T?
Yes, heading towards Highway 44.
How far past T are you?
I just pulled over as soon as I talked to you.
Okay. How old are you?
Alright, I'm going to get an ambulance on the way. What’s your name?
Larry.
Larry, do you have a history of heart problems?
Yeah, I'm taking medicine.
Do you have any aspirin with you?
No, I don't think so.
Alright. My partner has the ambulance on the way. You don’t have to talk to me, but I’ll stay on the line with you, okay?
Okay.
Did you just start feeling this way?
I've been feeling it for about 30 minutes. I just left a scrap yard in Franklin County, trying to untie my trailer, and felt tightness in the chest. I thought, better stop.
So you got back in your truck and turned the air conditioner on, but it’s not getting better?
No, it's not getting better.
Are you taking any other medications?
No.
Are you in your vehicle?
No, I'm sitting on the ground in front. I was going to try to lay down.
Okay, lie down if that makes you more comfortable.
I feel like somebody's sitting on my chest.
Try to take some deep breaths, Larry.
I'll try.
It's all right, Larry. The ambulance is on the way. Is anybody around to help you?
No one's stopping.
It's okay. Your wife will be relieved that you're getting help.
I don't want to call her. She'll be scared.
Don't worry, we won't call her now.
I'm not ready to go, I've got young grandkids.
It's alright, Larry. You're going to see Ryan and Lindsay soon. Stay with me.
I don't see anybody coming. My wife's going to kill me.
No, she won’t. She’ll just be glad that you’re okay.
Okay, I'll try.
What's your wife’s name?
Kathy.
Alright, Kathy and the grandkids will be glad you're getting help. Do you feel short of breath?
Yes.
Try to take some slow, deep breaths.
I don't think I'm going to make it.
Yes, you are. You're going to make it. Stay with me.
I see the ambulance, but they're too far away.
They're coming. Stay with me, Larry. Ryan and Lindsay are waiting for you.
I'll try.
Stay with me. Do you see them getting closer?
Yeah, they're almost here.
Alright, Larry. Help is almost there. Hang in there.
I see them.
Okay, good. Stay with me until they get to you.
They are here.
Okay, Larry. You're going to be fine. Let them take care of you. Bye.
